 the ennio morricone score that man can do no wrong.", :sentiment=>-1, :context_tags=>{:sound=>10}, :emphasis=>0.0, :people_tags=>[], :people_indexes=>[]}, {:index=>3, :text=>"A modern marvel.", :clean_text=>"a modern marvel.", :sentiment=>2, :context_tags=>{}, :emphasis=>0.0, :people_tags=>[], :people_indexes=>[]}]}, {:username=>"TomBowler", :useful=>"Super Reviewer", :date=>"August 1, 2009", :rating=>5, :percentage=>100.0, :content=>"Great acting, great script and some amazing direction. Full review later.", :title=>nil, :location=>nil, :source=>{:vendor=>"rotten_tomatoes", :url=>"http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_good_the_bad_and_the_ugly"}, :rescore_review=>[]}, {:username=>"Daniel P", :useful=>"Super Reviewer", :date=>"April 16, 2007", :rating=>5, :percentage=>100.0, :content=>"Simply stunning. The original three-part chase (eat your heart out, No Country For Old Men fans), Leone's final instalment in the Man With No Name trilogy is far and away the best one. This may be a perfect film. Take the already established operator Eastwood and singularly-focussed Van Cleef, then throw in an outstanding performance by Eli Wallach as Tuco, the man who - even more so than the above two, in the first two films - will do anything for a buck (or $200,000, in this case).\r\rThe score is the best of Morricone's three, and could probably tell the story by itself. The cinematography is colourful and lively and at the same shows the desolation in which this story. And in the middle is an encounter between Tuco and his brother that, in about four minutes of film, is one of the most subtle and profound meditations on loneliness I've ever seen. In fact, it explains the whole trilogy, each of the main characters, and maybe even the cultural figure of the lone rider that's become so prevalent in our art. (Recall Eastwood, who said around the time he made Unforgiven that of late, all movies are Westerns.)\r\rNow, add in a little touch of politics and history - the Civil War is ongoing - and a few good gun battles, especially the film's climax, and you have an absolute masterpiece. Up there with Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid as the best Western I've ever seen, and maybe the out-and-out best movie I've ever seen. A must, must, must. Beautiful piece of art that's often imitated but will never, ever be duplicated. Stunning.", :title=>nil, :location=>nil, :source=>{:vendor=>"rotten_tomatoes", :url=>"http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_good_the_bad_and_the_ugly"}, :rescore_review=>[{:index=>0, :text=>"Simply stunning.", :clean_text=>"simply stunning.", :sentiment=>2, :context_tags=>{}, :emphasis=>0.0, :people_tags=>[], :people_indexes=>[]}, {:index=>1, :text=>"The original three-part chase (eat your heart out, No Country For Old Men fans), Leone's final instalment in the Man With No Name trilogy is far and away the best one.", :clean_text=>"the original three-part chase eat your heart out no country for old men fans leone's final instalment in the man with no name trilogy is far and away the best one.", :sentiment=>2, :context_tags=>{:novelty=>100}, :emphasis=>0.0, :people_tags=>["Clint Eastwood"], :people_indexes=>[]}, {:index=>2, :text=>"This may be a perfect film.", :clean_text=>"this may be a perfect film.", :sentiment=>2, :context_tags=>{}, :emphasis=>0.0, :people_tags=>[], :people_indexes=>[]}, {:index=>3, :text=>"Take the already established operator Eastwood and singularly-focussed Van Cleef, then throw in an outstanding performance by Eli Wallach as Tuco, the man who - even more so than the above two, in the first two films - will do anything for a buck (or $200,000, in this case).", :clean_text=>"take the already established operator eastwood and singularly-focussed van cleef then throw in an outstanding performance by eli wallach as tuco the man who even more so than the above two in the first two films will do anything for a buck or 200,000 in this case).", :sentiment=>2, :context_tags=>{:cast=>90}, :emphasis=>1.0, :people_tags=>["E