t, but it's savvy enough to realise that our paths of thought and  modes of organisation are almost entirely contaminated by the world we've  created. Is the solution to destroy that world? Well, that's an option --  but watch closely in the movie's second half and see how subtly and  hilariously Fincher undermines this: the anarchists begin to chant  management-speak, to dissolve into a collective identity, and to form  franchises as if they were selling frappucino rather than revolution.  Norton is especially horrified at all this, and his wonderful reactions to  the disintegration of 'Project Mayhem' are the calm (and moral) centre of  the film. Rather like ANIMAL FARM, Fincher tells us that we can have our  revolution, but it's going to cost us dear; perhaps even the individuality  and reason which we'd hoped to gain from our actions.", :rating=>5.0, :percentage=>100.0, :useful=>[160, 179], :date=>" 2000 February 2", :title=>"The year's best satire", :location=>"(Princeton, NJ)", :username=>"\"pocock\"", :source=>{:vendor=>"amazon", :url=>"http://www.amazon.com/Fight-Club-Two-Disc-Collectors-Edition/product-reviews/B00003W8NM"}, :rescore_review=>[{:index=>0, :text=>"FIGHT CLUB arrived in the US with a blaze of publicity stressing its violence and nihilism; some critics (and those close to the production) countered this with the suggestion that it was an anti-materialist  jeremiad.", :clean_text=>"fight club arrived in the us with a blaze of publicity stressing its violence and nihilism some critics and those close to the production countered this with the suggestion that it was an anti-materialist jeremiad.", :sentiment=>-2, :context_tags=>{:cinematography=>80}, :emphasis=>3.0, :people_tags=>[], :people_indexes=>[]}, {:index=>1, :text=>"On a second viewing, it seems like neither -- it's easier to see  it as a smart, committed and complex piece of filmmaking.", :clean_text=>"on a second viewing it seems like neither it's easier to see it as a smart committed and 